    <name>Reasoning to Find Area - Student Work Samples</name>
    <intro>&lt;h3&gt;Introduction&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"&gt;We can use the “decompose and rearrange” and “enclose and subtract” strategies for finding area to extend the formula for area of any rectangle to derive a formula for area of any parallelogram, and then to derive the formula for the area of any triangle.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"&gt;Recall how those strategies were used in the &lt;em&gt;Reasoning to Find Area&lt;/em&gt; activity in Session&amp;nbsp;5.1.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"&gt;Below are some ways students might have found the areas of the shaded regions. Ideally, we can use students’ ways of thinking as formative assessment, and make instructional decisions in later lessons.&lt;/p&gt;
